</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="86" pageNumber="87" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
The adpressed pubescent, lanceolate to strap-shaped leaves combined with the small corolla are characteristic. Flower size and usually leaf shape serve to distinguish it from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pers., Syn. Pl. 1: 180. 1805. (Persoon" authorityYear="1805" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus chilensis" order="Solanales" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chilensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Convolvulus chilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with which it sometimes grows in Chile. It is morphologically extraordinarily similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Engl., Abh. Koenigl. Akad. Wiss. Berlin 2: 349. 1892. (Engler" authorityYear="1892" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus aschersonii" order="Solanales" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aschersonii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Convolvulus aschersonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from South Africa which differs in its paler, more deeply lobed corollas and usually shorter sepals.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
